SIMPLE: flannel
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Flannel
<hw>Flan"nel</hw> <pr>(fl⟦acr⟧n"n⟦ecr⟧l)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>flanelle</ets>, cf. OF. <ets>flaine</ets> a pillowcase, a mattress
(?); fr. W. <ets>gwlanen</ets> flannel, fr. <ets>gwlan</ets> wool; prob.
akin to E. <ets>wool</ets>. Cf. <er>Wool</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A
soft, nappy, woolen cloth, of loose texture.</def>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>a cotton fabric with a thick nap on one side,
resembling flannel{1}; it is used, <it>e. g.</it> for underwear or
sheets; also called <altname>flannelette</altname>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <pluf>pl.</pluf> <def>garments made of flannel,
especially underwear.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>a washcloth.</def> <mark>[Brit.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>humbug; nonsensical or evasive talk.</def>
<mark>[Brit. informal]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>insincere flattery or praise.</def> <mark>[Brit.
informal]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Adam's flannel</b></col>. <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <cd>See under
<er>Adam</er>.</cd> -- <mcol><col><b>Canton flannel</b></col>,
<col><b>Cotton flannel</b></col></mcol>. <cd>See <cref>Cotton
flannel</cref>, under <er>Cotton</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>flannelbush</ent>⟦br⟧
<ent>flannelbush</ent>⟦br⟧
